\f0\b\fs44 \cf0 Italian Sausage:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sl400\ql\qnatural
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs42 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}2 pounds pork shoulder (with a good amount of fat), cut into large chunks\
{\listtext	\'95	}2 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/garlic/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cloves garlic}}, minced\
{\listtext	\'95	}2 tablespoons kosher salt\
{\listtext	\'95	}1 tablespoon fennel seed\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/2 tablespoon crushed red pepper\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/2 tablespoon ground coriander\
{\listtext	\'95	}Ice cold water\
{\listtext	\'95	}Oil\
{\listtext	\'95	}Hog casing\
{\listtext	\'95	}Special equipment: stand {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/mixer/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 mixer}} with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/meat-grinder/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 meat grinder}} and sausage horn attachments\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\sa140\ql\qnatural
\cf0 Place the pork shoulder in a bowl and keep cold until ready to use. Fill a large bowl with ice and place the bowl with the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/pork-shoulder/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 pork shoulder}} on top.\
Season the pork with garlic, salt, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/fennel-seed/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 fennel seed}}, crushed red pepper, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/coriander/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 coriander}}. Mix to combine well.\
Grind the pork shoulder twice through a grinding disk with large holes. Grind the meat into the bowl sitting on ice.\
Cook a small amount of the meat mixture to test for seasoning. Add more {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/spices/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 spices}} and salt, if needed. Thoroughly mix in a splash of cold water. Allow the seasoned pork to chill on ice or in the fridge before {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/stuffing/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 stuffing}} into the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/casing/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 casing}}.\
Replace the grinder attachment with the horn. (Be sure to thoroughly clean the attachment area before proceeding.) Rub oil onto the horn, and then put the casing on, leaving a few inches of slack at the end.\
Stuff the casing, tie off the ends, and prick the sausage with a pin or the tip of a knife.\
Refrigerate the sausage until ready to cook.\
